        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Parasite SEO</strong> is the practice of publishing keyword-optimised content on high-authority third-party platforms — such as Medium, LinkedIn articles, Reddit, or news sites with contributor programs — to rank for competitive queries using that platform's existing domain authority. Instead of building organic authority on an owned domain, parasite SEO rents rankings on someone else's domain. Google introduced a specific site reputation abuse policy in November 2024 directly targeting this practice.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Google policy</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Site reputation abuse (Nov 2024)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Risk level</div>
            <div class="tms-value">High (post-2024)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Parasite SEO is one of the most debated tactics in search marketing — it works until it doesn't, and since November 2024, "doesn't" has become the dominant outcome. Understanding exactly how it functions, why Google targeted it, and what the sustainable alternative looks like matters whether you are trying to avoid it or evaluate whether a competitor is using it against you.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is parasite SEO?</h2>
        <p>The term comes from the biological concept: a parasite lives on a host organism, using its resources without building its own. In SEO, the "host" is a high-authority domain (Medium, Forbes, CNN, a major news site with a contributor program) and the "parasite" is the low-effort affiliate or promotional content placed there to rank for competitive keywords.</p>
        <p>The mechanism exploits a real ranking signal. Google uses domain authority — the accumulated trust of a domain based on its age, backlink profile, and history of quality content — as a component of ranking. A page published on a domain with 15 years of editorial content and thousands of editorial backlinks starts with a significant ranking advantage over a page on a new domain with no backlinks.</p>
        <p>Parasite SEO exploits this by placing ranking-optimised content on the high-authority host rather than building a domain from scratch.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's November 2024 site reputation abuse policy</div>
          <p>Google explicitly defined "site reputation abuse" as third-party content produced primarily for ranking purposes on an otherwise-trusted site. The policy targets both the content and the host platform. Sites hosting this content face ranking penalties for the specific pages or, in severe cases, their entire domain. Major publishers (Forbes, CNN, Fortune) have scaled back third-party contributor programs that enabled this practice.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why parasite SEO matters for search marketers</h2>
        <p>Whether or not you practice parasite SEO, it has three direct implications for anyone doing search marketing:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>You may be competing against it.</strong> If you rank position 3 for a keyword and position 1 is a Medium article written by an affiliate marketer with no genuine expertise, that is parasite SEO. Understanding the tactic helps identify which competitors are building durable rankings versus which are renting borrowed authority.</li>
          <li><strong>It shapes which platforms you trust for backlinks.</strong> The same high-DA platforms exploited for parasite SEO are often used in link building outreach. A backlink from Forbes carries less ranking weight when that site's editorial standards have been diluted by paid contributor placements.</li>
          <li><strong>Google's enforcement is real but imperfect.</strong> Parasite SEO still exists in search results in 2026, but at significantly reduced scale post-November 2024. Understanding the enforcement mechanisms helps predict which types of competitor content will be penalised and which will persist.</li>
          <li><strong>The alternative is directly better.</strong> Every argument for parasite SEO — speed to ranking, competitive keyword access — can be answered by owned authority built at sufficient publishing velocity. The difference is the time horizon and capital required.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How parasite SEO works — the playbook</h2>
        <p>The parasite SEO playbook has four steps. Understanding them precisely helps identify it when competitors use it and evaluate whether Google's enforcement has caught a specific instance:</p>

        <h3>Step 1: Identify the host platform</h3>
        <p>Find high-authority domains that accept user-generated or third-party content with minimal editorial oversight. Categories: publishing platforms (Medium, Substack), professional networks (LinkedIn articles), Q&A sites (Quora, Reddit), UGC sites (YouTube, SlideShare), and news sites with contributor programs.</p>

        <h3>Step 2: Identify the target keyword</h3>
        <p>Find a competitive keyword where the organic results contain pages with weak on-page optimisation but high-DA domain backing. Typical targets: affiliate queries ("best [product category] 2026"), high-commission financial or health terms, and local service queries where local competition has weak content.</p>

        <h3>Step 3: Publish keyword-optimised content</h3>
        <p>Produce content optimised for the target keyword and publish it on the chosen host platform. The host domain's authority does most of the ranking work. The content itself may be thin, affiliate-heavy, or lacking genuine expertise.</p>

        <h3>Step 4: Monetise the ranking</h3>
        <p>Once ranked, the page generates affiliate commissions, lead capture, or traffic to a separate commercial site. The host platform receives no share of this monetisation — hence the parasite metaphor.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Parasite SEO vs legitimate third-party content — where's the line?</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Parasite SEO</th><th>Legitimate third-party content</th></tr>
